{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01HpuUbrS3jKtZDoyxBM1Z9q","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.domain.model.cargo;\n     2→\n     3→import java.io.Serializable;\n     4→import jakarta.persistence.Embedded;\n     5→import jakarta.persistence.Entity;\n     6→import jakarta.persistence.GeneratedValue;\n     7→import jakarta.persistence.Id;\n     8→import jakarta.persistence.JoinColumn;\n     9→import jakarta.persistence.ManyToOne;\n    10→import jakarta.persistence.NamedQuery;\n    11→import jakarta.validation.constraints.NotNull;\n    12→import org.apache.commons.lang3.Validate;\n    13→import org.eclipse.cargotracker.domain.model.handling.HandlingEvent;\n    14→import org.eclipse.cargotracker.domain.model.handling.HandlingHistory;\n    15→import org.eclipse.cargotracker.domain.model.location.Location;\n    16→import org.eclipse.cargotracker.domain.shared.DomainObjectUtils;\n    17→\n    18→/**\n    19→ * A Cargo. This is the central class in the domain model, and it is the root of the\n    20→ * Cargo-Itinerary-Leg-Delivery-RouteSpecification aggregate.\n    21→ *\n    22→ * <p>\n    23→ * A cargo is identified by a unique tracking ID, and it always has an origin and a route\n    24→ * specification. The life cycle of a cargo begins with the booking procedure, when the tracking ID\n    25→ * is assigned. During a (short) period of time, between booking and initial routing, the cargo has\n    26→ * no itinerary.\n    27→ *\n    28→ * <p>\n    29→ * The booking clerk requests a list of possible routes, matching the route specification, and\n    30→ * assigns the cargo to one route. The route to which a cargo is assigned is described by an\n    31→ * itinerary.\n    32→ *\n    33→ * <p>\n    34→ * A cargo can be re-routed during transport, on demand of the customer, in which case a new route\n    35→ * is specified for the cargo and a new route is requested. The old itinerary, being a value object,\n    36→ * is discarded and a new one is attached.\n    37→ *\n    38→ * <p>\n    39→ * It may also happen that a cargo is accidentally misrouted, which should notify the proper\n    40→ * personnel and also trigger a re-routing procedure.\n    41→ *\n    42→ * <p>\n    43→ * When a cargo is handled, the status of the delivery changes. Everything about the delivery of the\n    44→ * cargo is contained in the Delivery value object, which is replaced whenever a cargo is handled by\n    45→ * an asynchronous event triggered by the registration of the handling event.\n    46→ *\n    47→ * <p>\n    48→ * The delivery can also be affected by routing changes, i.e. when a the route specification\n    49→ * changes, or the cargo is assigned to a new route. In that case, the delivery update is performed\n    50→ * synchronously within the cargo aggregate.\n    51→ *\n    52→ * <p>\n    53→ * The life cycle of a cargo ends when the cargo is claimed by the customer.\n    54→ *\n    55→ * <p>\n    56→ * The cargo aggregate, and the entire domain model, is built to solve the problem of booking and\n    57→ * tracking cargo. All important business rules for determining whether or not a cargo is\n    58→ * misdirected, what the current status of the cargo is (on board carrier, in port etc), are\n    59→ * captured in this aggregate.\n    60→ */\n    61→@Entity\n    62→@NamedQuery(\n    63→    name = \"Cargo.findByTrackingId\",\n    64→    query = \"Select c from Cargo c where c.trackingId = :trackingId\")\n    65→public class Cargo implements Serializable {\n    66→\n    67→  private static final long serialVersionUID = 1L;\n    68→\n    69→  @Id\n    70→  @GeneratedValue\n    71→  private Long id;\n    72→\n    73→  @Embedded\n    74→  @NotNull(message = \"Tracking ID is required.\")\n    75→  private TrackingId trackingId;\n    76→\n    77→  @ManyToOne\n    78→  @JoinColumn(name = \"origin_id\", updatable = false)\n    79→  @NotNull\n    80→  private Location origin;\n    81→\n    82→  @Embedded\n    83→  @NotNull(message = \"Route specification is required.\")\n    84→  private RouteSpecification routeSpecification;\n    85→\n    86→  @Embedded\n    87→  @NotNull\n    88→  private Itinerary itinerary;\n    89→  @Embedded\n    90→  @NotNull\n    91→  private Delivery delivery;\n    92→\n    93→  public Cargo() {\n    94→    // Nothing to initialize.\n    95→  }\n    96→\n    97→  public Cargo(TrackingId trackingId, RouteSpecification routeSpecification) {\n    98→    Validate.notNull(trackingId, \"Tracking ID is required.\");\n    99→    Validate.notNull(routeSpecification, \"Route specification is required.\");\n   100→\n   101→    this.trackingId = trackingId;\n   102→    // Cargo origin never changes, even if the route specification changes.\n   103→    // However, at creation, cargo origin can be derived from the initial\n   104→    // route specification.\n   105→    this.origin = routeSpecification.getOrigin();\n   106→    this.routeSpecification = routeSpecification;\n   107→\n   108→    this.delivery =\n   109→        Delivery.derivedFrom(this.routeSpecification, this.itinerary, HandlingHistory.EMPTY);\n   110→    this.itinerary = Itinerary.EMPTY_ITINERARY;\n   111→  }\n   112→\n   113→  public TrackingId getTrackingId() {\n   114→    return trackingId;\n   115→  }\n   116→\n   117→  public Location getOrigin() {\n   118→    return origin;\n   119→  }\n   120→\n   121→  public void setOrigin(Location origin) {\n   122→    this.origin = origin;\n   123→  }\n   124→\n   125→  public RouteSpecification getRouteSpecification() {\n   126→    return routeSpecification;\n   127→  }\n   128→\n   129→  /** @return The delivery. Never null. */\n   130→  public Delivery getDelivery() {\n   131→    return delivery;\n   132→  }\n   133→\n   134→  /** @return The itinerary. Never null. */\n   135→  public Itinerary getItinerary() {\n   136→    return DomainObjectUtils.nullSafe(this.itinerary, Itinerary.EMPTY_ITINERARY);\n   137→  }\n   138→\n   139→  /** Specifies a new route for this cargo. */\n   140→  public void specifyNewRoute(RouteSpecification routeSpecification) {\n   141→    Validate.notNull(routeSpecification, \"Route specification is required.\");\n   142→\n   143→    this.routeSpecification = routeSpecification;\n   144→    // Handling consistency within the Cargo aggregate synchronously\n   145→    this.delivery = delivery.updateOnRouting(this.routeSpecification, this.itinerary);\n   146→  }\n   147→\n   148→  public void assignToRoute(Itinerary itinerary) {\n   149→    Validate.notNull(itinerary, \"Itinerary is required for assignment.\");\n   150→\n   151→    this.itinerary = itinerary;\n   152→    // Handling consistency within the Cargo aggregate synchronously\n   153→    this.delivery = delivery.updateOnRouting(this.routeSpecification, this.itinerary);\n   154→  }\n   155→\n   156→  /**\n   157→   * Updates all aspects of the cargo aggregate status based on the current route specification,\n   158→   * itinerary and handling of the cargo.\n   159→   *\n   160→   * <p>\n   161→   * When either of those three changes, i.e. when a new route is specified for the cargo, the cargo\n   162→   * is assigned to a route or when the cargo is handled, the status must be re-calculated.\n   163→   *\n   164→   * <p>\n   165→   * {@link RouteSpecification} and {@link Itinerary} are both inside the Cargo aggregate, so\n   166→   * changes to them cause the status to be updated <b>synchronously</b>, but changes to the\n   167→   * delivery history (when a cargo is handled) cause the status update to happen\n   168→   * <b>asynchronously</b> since {@link HandlingEvent} is in a different aggregate.\n   169→   *\n   170→   * @param handlingHistory handling history\n   171→   */\n   172→  public void deriveDeliveryProgress(HandlingHistory handlingHistory) {\n   173→    this.delivery = Delivery.derivedFrom(getRouteSpecification(), getItinerary(), handlingHistory);\n   174→  }\n   175→\n   176→  /**\n   177→   * @param object to compare\n   178→   * @return True if they have the same identity\n   179→   * @see #sameIdentityAs(Cargo)\n   180→   */\n   181→  @Override\n   182→  public boolean equals(Object object) {\n   183→    if (this == object) {\n   184→      return true;\n   185→    }\n   186→    if (object == null || !(object instanceof Cargo)) {\n   187→      return false;\n   188→    }\n   189→\n   190→    Cargo other = (Cargo) object;\n   191→    return sameIdentityAs(other);\n   192→  }\n   193→\n   194→  private boolean sameIdentityAs(Cargo other) {\n   195→    return other != null && trackingId.sameValueAs(other.trackingId);\n   196→  }\n   197→\n   198→  /** @return Hash code of tracking id. */\n   199→  @Override\n   200→  public int hashCode() {\n   201→    return trackingId.hashCode();\n   202→  }\n   203→\n   204→  @Override\n   205→  public String toString() {\n   206→    return trackingId.toString();\n   207→  }\n   208→}\n   209→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_018JHt2ULGGkJoNbU4yYVNzA","session_id":"6fabce19-5bc2-4de5-94d2-1fb45743d165","uuid":"814fc9ad-1899-4eac-8a56-a8fbb034a8fb"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01Pcn5HHuSaW6hkgYzPykpKa","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.domain.shared;\n     2→\n     3→/**\n     4→ * OR specification, used to create a new specification that is the OR of two other specifications.\n     5→ */\n     6→public class OrSpecification<T> extends AbstractSpecification<T> {\n     7→\n     8→  private final Specification<T> spec1;\n     9→  private final Specification<T> spec2;\n    10→\n    11→  /**\n    12→   * Create a new OR specification based on two other spec.\n    13→   *\n    14→   * @param spec1 Specification one.\n    15→   * @param spec2 Specification two.\n    16→   */\n    17→  public OrSpecification(Specification<T> spec1, Specification<T> spec2) {\n    18→    this.spec1 = spec1;\n    19→    this.spec2 = spec2;\n    20→  }\n    21→\n    22→  /** {@inheritDoc} */\n    23→  @Override\n    24→  public boolean isSatisfiedBy(T t) {\n    25→    return spec1.isSatisfiedBy(t) || spec2.isSatisfiedBy(t);\n    26→  }\n    27→}\n    28→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_018JHt2ULGGkJoNbU4yYVNzA","session_id":"6fabce19-5bc2-4de5-94d2-1fb45743d165","uuid":"89f4eda7-6489-4c29-83ec-19faf4cfba50"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01DcXKW5jxTLowkskvt6Lhop","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.domain.shared;\n     2→\n     3→/**\n     4→ * Specification interface.\n     5→ *\n     6→ * <p>Use {@link AbstractSpecification} as base for creating specifications, and only the method\n     7→ * {@link #isSatisfiedBy(Object)} must be implemented.\n     8→ */\n     9→public interface Specification<T> {\n    10→\n    11→  /**\n    12→   * Check if {@code t} is satisfied by the specification.\n    13→   *\n    14→   * @param t Object to test.\n    15→   * @return {@code true} if {@code t} satisfies the specification.\n    16→   */\n    17→  boolean isSatisfiedBy(T t);\n    18→\n    19→  /**\n    20→   * Create a new specification that is the AND operation of {@code this} specification and another\n    21→   * specification.\n    22→   *\n    23→   * @param specification Specification to AND.\n    24→   * @return A new specification.\n    25→   */\n    26→  Specification<T> and(Specification<T> specification);\n    27→\n    28→  /**\n    29→   * Create a new specification that is the OR operation of {@code this} specification and another\n    30→   * specification.\n    31→   *\n    32→   * @param specification Specification to OR.\n    33→   * @return A new specification.\n    34→   */\n    35→  Specification<T> or(Specification<T> specification);\n    36→\n    37→  /**\n    38→   * Create a new specification that is the NOT operation of {@code this} specification.\n    39→   *\n    40→   * @param specification Specification to NOT.\n    41→   * @return A new specification.\n    42→   */\n    43→  Specification<T> not(Specification<T> specification);\n    44→}\n    45→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_018JHt2ULGGkJoNbU4yYVNzA","session_id":"6fabce19-5bc2-4de5-94d2-1fb45743d165","uuid":"aba69496-cf9b-41b8-aea9-053bd02a321a"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_019BWxsbTwnf6zNZTeYdnKJ9","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.domain.shared;\n     2→\n     3→/** NOT decorator, used to create a new specifcation that is the inverse (NOT) of the given spec. */\n     4→public class NotSpecification<T> extends AbstractSpecification<T> {\n     5→\n     6→  private final Specification<T> spec1;\n     7→\n     8→  /**\n     9→   * Create a new NOT specification based on another spec.\n    10→   *\n    11→   * @param spec1 Specification instance to not.\n    12→   */\n    13→  public NotSpecification(Specification<T> spec1) {\n    14→    this.spec1 = spec1;\n    15→  }\n    16→\n    17→  /** {@inheritDoc} */\n    18→  @Override\n    19→  public boolean isSatisfiedBy(T t) {\n    20→    return !spec1.isSatisfiedBy(t);\n    21→  }\n    22→}\n    23→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_018JHt2ULGGkJoNbU4yYVNzA","session_id":"6fabce19-5bc2-4de5-94d2-1fb45743d165","uuid":"d40a1477-71fe-4481-8e70-9bf5d44d2870"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01CudsHF9AJ336ATawKqx7wJ","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.domain.shared;\n     2→\n     3→/**\n     4→ * Abstract base implementation of composite {@link Specification} with default implementations for\n     5→ * {@code and}, {@code or} and {@code not}.\n     6→ */\n     7→public abstract class AbstractSpecification<T> implements Specification<T> {\n     8→\n     9→  /** {@inheritDoc} */\n    10→  @Override\n    11→  public abstract boolean isSatisfiedBy(T t);\n    12→\n    13→  /** {@inheritDoc} */\n    14→  @Override\n    15→  public Specification<T> and(Specification<T> specification) {\n    16→    return new AndSpecification<>(this, specification);\n    17→  }\n    18→\n    19→  /** {@inheritDoc} */\n    20→  @Override\n    21→  public Specification<T> or(Specification<T> specification) {\n    22→    return new OrSpecification<>(this, specification);\n    23→  }\n    24→\n    25→  /** {@inheritDoc} */\n    26→  @Override\n    27→  public Specification<T> not(Specification<T> specification) {\n    28→    return new NotSpecification<>(specification);\n    29→  }\n    30→}\n    31→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_018JHt2ULGGkJoNbU4yYVNzA","session_id":"6fabce19-5bc2-4de5-94d2-1fb45743d165","uuid":"85d6ba32-a048-4a0a-a385-5a3361567393"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01Nz8NPexngerUfUM9RSQiye","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.domain.shared;\n     2→\n     3→// TODO [Clean Code] Make this a CDI singleton?\n     4→public class DomainObjectUtils {\n     5→\n     6→  /** Prevent instantiation. */\n     7→  private DomainObjectUtils() {}\n     8→\n     9→  /**\n    10→   * @param actual actual value\n    11→   * @param safe a null-safe value\n    12→   * @param <T> type\n    13→   * @return actual value, if it's not null, or safe value if the actual value is null.\n    14→   */\n    15→  public static <T> T nullSafe(T actual, T safe) {\n    16→    return actual == null ? safe : actual;\n    17→  }\n    18→}\n    19→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_018JHt2ULGGkJoNbU4yYVNzA","session_id":"6fabce19-5bc2-4de5-94d2-1fb45743d165","uuid":"5efa0103-cc25-4196-a649-7249eb06082a"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01AHsxMeAX5yHzJsQtQL7XcQ","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.domain.shared;\n     2→\n     3→/**\n     4→ * AND specification, used to create a new specification that is the AND of two other\n     5→ * specifications.\n     6→ */\n     7→public class AndSpecification<T> extends AbstractSpecification<T> {\n     8→\n     9→  private final Specification<T> spec1;\n    10→  private final Specification<T> spec2;\n    11→\n    12→  /**\n    13→   * Create a new AND specification based on two other spec.\n    14→   *\n    15→   * @param spec1 Specification one.\n    16→   * @param spec2 Specification two.\n    17→   */\n    18→  public AndSpecification(Specification<T> spec1, Specification<T> spec2) {\n    19→    this.spec1 = spec1;\n    20→    this.spec2 = spec2;\n    21→  }\n    22→\n    23→  /** {@inheritDoc} */\n    24→  @Override\n    25→  public boolean isSatisfiedBy(T t) {\n    26→    return spec1.isSatisfiedBy(t) && spec2.isSatisfiedBy(t);\n    27→  }\n    28→}\n    29→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_018JHt2ULGGkJoNbU4yYVNzA","session_id":"6fabce19-5bc2-4de5-94d2-1fb45743d165","uuid":"7661afae-807a-4e50-b009-f515b5d7dfa0"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01K8nzrdMMJkdmTGMusinnrS","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.domain.service;\n     2→\n     3→import java.util.List;\n     4→import org.eclipse.cargotracker.domain.model.cargo.Itinerary;\n     5→import org.eclipse.cargotracker.domain.model.cargo.RouteSpecification;\n     6→\n     7→public interface RoutingService {\n     8→\n     9→  /**\n    10→   * @param routeSpecification Route specification\n    11→   * @return A list of itineraries that satisfy the specification. May be an empty list if no route\n    12→   *     is found.\n    13→   */\n    14→  List<Itinerary> fetchRoutesForSpecification(RouteSpecification routeSpecification);\n    15→}\n    16→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_018JHt2ULGGkJoNbU4yYVNzA","session_id":"6fabce19-5bc2-4de5-94d2-1fb45743d165","uuid":"2044a3a8-5953-41ad-a799-8c0eb9c58a45"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01PNUZj2oBKFtHgLM9RwYbyu","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.infrastructure.events.cdi;\n     2→\n     3→import static java.lang.annotation.ElementType.FIELD;\n     4→import static java.lang.annotation.ElementType.PARAMETER;\n     5→import static java.lang.annotation.RetentionPolicy.RUNTIME;\n     6→\n     7→import java.lang.annotation.Retention;\n     8→import java.lang.annotation.Target;\n     9→import jakarta.inject.Qualifier;\n    10→\n    11→@Qualifier\n    12→@Retention(RUNTIME)\n    13→@Target({FIELD, PARAMETER})\n    14→public @interface CargoUpdated {\n    15→}\n    16→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_018JHt2ULGGkJoNbU4yYVNzA","session_id":"6fabce19-5bc2-4de5-94d2-1fb45743d165","uuid":"9a02d453-e39e-4581-be7e-4bb813e49fde"}
